+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DM9WXtGxHibqBkVnk3SsJM","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All tests pass, TypeScript compiles cleanly, and lint passes. Now let me do a thorough deep-dive review of the implementation.\n\n---\n\n## Code Review: Constraint-Based Event Scheduler\n\n### Overall Assessment\n\nAll 30 tests pass, the project compiles without errors, and lint is clean. The implementation in `/workspace/src/index.ts` is a reasonable solution that uses a multi-strategy greedy approach combined with a bounded backtracking solver. The test suite in `/workspace/src/scheduler.test.ts` covers the major requirements well. That said, I have identified several issues -- some of which are correctness bugs that could surface with inputs not covered by the current tests, and others that are structural or performance concerns.\n\n---\n\n### 1. CRITICAL: Gap Symmetry Bug in `findEarliestSlot` and `findEarliestSlotArr`\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 174 and 553\n\nBoth slot-finding functions use this overlap check:\n\n```typescript\nif (candidateStart < slot.end + gap && candidateEnd > slot.start - gap) {\n```\n\nThe condition `candidateEnd > slot.start - gap` is incorrect. The gap is a minimum spacing between the *end* of one event and the *start* of the next. It should not be applied symmetrically on both sides of existing slots. The correct check for whether a candidate conflicts with an existing slot (i.e., they are closer than `gap` apart) is:\n\n```typescript\nif (candidateStart < slot.end + gap && candidateEnd + gap > slot.start) {\n```\n\nOr equivalently, the non-overlapping condition should be:\n- candidate ends before slot starts (with gap): `candidateEnd + gap <= slot.start`\n- candidate starts after slot ends (with gap): `candidateStart >= slot.end + gap`\n\nThe current code subtracts `gap` from `slot.start`, which means if a candidate event tries to fit *before* an existing event, it must end `gap` minutes before the existing event starts -- that part is correct in intent. But the issue is subtle: consider `candidateEnd > slot.start - gap`. If `gap = 0`, this correctly checks for strict non-overlap. But when `gap > 0`, the expression `slot.start - gap` can cause the algorithm to reject valid placements or, more importantly, it treats the gap as needing to be enforced on *both* sides when the algorithm then pushes `candidateStart = slot.end + gap`, effectively double-counting the gap constraint in certain edge cases.\n\nIn practice, this is likely masked because the algorithm always starts from `earliestStart` and moves forward, so it predominantly encounters the `candidateStart < slot.end + gap` branch. However, if events are not placed in chronological order (which can happen in the backtracking solver), a candidate that should fit into a gap *before* an existing event may be incorrectly rejected.\n\n**Recommendation:** Replace the overlap check with the clearer form:\n\n```typescript\nif (candidateStart < slot.end + gap && candidateEnd > slot.start - gap) {\n```\n\nShould be:\n\n```typescript\nif (!(candidateEnd + gap <= slot.start || candidateStart >= slot.end + gap)) {\n```\n\nWhich simplifies to:\n\n```typescript\nif (candidateEnd + gap > slot.start && candidateStart < slot.end + gap) {\n```\n\nThis ensures the gap is applied symmetrically and correctly: the candidate must be at least `gap` minutes away from any existing slot on either side.\n\n---\n\n### 2. CRITICAL: Backtracking `timeline.pop()` Assumes Last-In-First-Out Ordering\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, line 477\n\n```typescript\ntimeline.push({ start: slotStart, end: slotStart + event.duration });\n// ... recursive call ...\nassignments.delete(event.id);\ntimeline.pop();\n```\n\nThe backtracking solver adds a slot with `timeline.push(...)` and removes it with `timeline.pop()`. This only works correctly if the most recently pushed slot is always the last element -- i.e., no other slot is pushed on top of it before the pop occurs. In the recursive `solve` call, the function iterates over `schedulable` events and for each one tries multiple rooms. When a slot is pushed and then `solve` recurses, the recursive call could push additional slots on the *same* timeline array. Those recursive slots are popped within their own frames, so by the time control returns, the pushed slot should indeed be the last element.\n\nThis is actually correct due to the stack-based recursion pattern: each recursive frame pushes, recurses deeper (which pushes and pops its own slots), then pops. However, there is a subtle issue: the code iterates over `schedulable` events in a `for` loop and tries each one. When it places event A in room X and recurses, the recursive call might also try to place event B in room X (pushing onto the same timeline). But event B's slot is popped before returning, so event A's slot remains last. This is correct.\n\n**Verdict:** This is actually safe, but it is fragile. A comment explaining why `pop()` is valid here would improve maintainability.\n\n---\n\n### 3. IMPORTANT: Topological Sort Comparison is Unstable/Redundant\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 289-297\n\n```typescript\nconst orderedEvents = [...sortedEvents].sort((a, b) => {\n  const idxA = sortedEvents.indexOf(a);\n  const idxB = sortedEvents.indexOf(b);\n  if (idxA !== idxB) return idxA - idxB;\n  const depA = dependentCount.get(a.id) || 0;\n  const depB = dependentCount.get(b.id) || 0;\n  if (depA !== depB) return depB - depA;\n  return b.duration - a.duration;\n});\n```\n\nThe `indexOf` comparison will always return different values for different objects (assuming no duplicates), so the first branch `if (idxA !== idxB) return idxA - idxB` will always be taken. The dependent count and duration tiebreakers are dead code. This means the \"ordering\" by dependent count that `greedySchedule` computes (lines 206-239, including a BFS for every event) is entirely wasted computation.\n\nTo actually use the tiebreakers, the events at the same topological level need to be identified. One approach: assign a topological \"depth\" to each event and sort by depth first, then by dependent count and duration within the same depth.\n\n**Recommendation:** Either remove the dead-code tiebreaker logic or fix the sort to use topological depth rather than array index.\n\n---\n\n### 4. IMPORTANT: `topologicalSort` Has O(n^2) Performance Due to `queue.sort()` Inside the Loop\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, line 106\n\n```typescript\nwhile (queue.length > 0) {\n  queue.sort();\n  const id = queue.shift()!;\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\nSorting the queue on every iteration converts Kahn's algorithm from O(V+E) to O(V^2 log V). For the 15-event cap on backtracking this is irrelevant, but it is poor algorithmic practice. The sort also has no clear purpose -- it lexicographically orders event IDs, which produces deterministic output but is not a meaningful scheduling heuristic.\n\n**Recommendation:** Use a priority queue or simply remove the sort if determinism is not a requirement.\n\n---\n\n### 5. IMPORTANT: Backtracking is Gated Behind `sortedEvents.length <= 15`\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, line 522\n\n```typescript\nif (sortedEvents.length <= 15) {\n  solve([...sortedEvents]);\n}\n```\n\nFor inputs with more than 15 events, the backtracking solver is silently skipped, meaning the \"batch optimization\" requirement (maximizing scheduled events) relies entirely on the three greedy strategies. This is a pragmatic performance tradeoff, but it should be documented. The task requirement states: \"The scheduler should maximize the number of events scheduled. Simply fitting events in order is not sufficient.\" For large inputs, the greedy-only approach may not maximize scheduled events.\n\n**Recommendation:** Add a comment explaining the tradeoff. Consider a middle ground such as applying backtracking only to the subset of events that failed greedy scheduling (rather than all events).\n\n---\n\n### 6. IMPORTANT: `greedySchedule` Recomputes Transitive Dependents Inefficiently\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 226-239\n\n```typescript\nfor (const e of sortedEvents) {\n  const visited = new Set<string>();\n  const queue = [e.id];\n  while (queue.length > 0) {\n    const curr = queue.shift()!;\n    for (const dep of reverseDeps.get(curr) || []) {\n      if (!visited.has(dep)) {\n        visited.add(dep);\n        queue.push(dep);\n      }\n    }\n  }\n  dependentCount.set(e.id, visited.size);\n}\n```\n\nThis computes a BFS from every event to count transitive dependents -- O(V * (V+E)) in the worst case. Since the result is never actually used (see issue 3), this is wasted work. If the tiebreaker is fixed, a simple in-degree count or depth-based approach would suffice and be more efficient.\n\n---\n\n### 7. SUGGESTION: Preferred Room Logic May Prematurely Break in Backtracking\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 489-490\n\n```typescript\n// For preferred room, if it worked, don't try others\nif (room.id === event.preferredRoom) break;\n```\n\nIn the backtracking solver, when the preferred room works, the code breaks out of the room loop immediately. This means the solver never explores alternative room placements for this event, even if placing it in a non-preferred room might allow more total events to be scheduled. Since the task states that `preferredRoom` is \"a hint, not a hard constraint,\" the optimization goal (maximize events) should take priority over room preference in the backtracking solver.\n\n**Recommendation:** Remove this `break` in the backtracking solver to allow full exploration, or at least try the preferred room first but still explore alternatives.\n\n---\n\n### 8. SUGGESTION: Missing Test Coverage for Edge Cases\n\nThe test suite is solid but misses a few scenarios:\n\n- **Gap between prerequisite and dependent across different rooms**: The test at line 202 uses two rooms, but does not verify that the gap is applied even when the prerequisite and dependent are in *different* rooms. (The implementation does handle this correctly, but a test would confirm the intent.)\n\n- **Multiple prerequisites for a single event**: The complex scenario test has this (closing depends on workshop and breakout), but there is no isolated unit test for multiple prerequisites where the latest-finishing prerequisite determines the start time.\n\n- **Events with 0-minute duration**: The task does not prohibit it, and the scheduler would likely handle it, but no test exercises this boundary.\n\n- **All events unschedulable**: A test where every event exceeds every room's capacity would verify the \"everything goes to unscheduled\" path.\n\n- **Preferred room that does not exist**: An event referencing a `preferredRoom` ID that is not in the rooms list. The current implementation handles this gracefully (the preference is simply ignored), but a test would document this behavior.\n\n---\n\n### 9. SUGGESTION: Code Duplication Between `findEarliestSlot` and `findEarliestSlotArr`\n\n**Files:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 147-191 and 537-566\n\nThese two functions are nearly identical. The only difference is that `findEarliestSlot` takes a `RoomTimeline` object while `findEarliestSlotArr` takes a raw array. The `RoomTimeline` wrapper adds no value since it just wraps a `slots` array.\n\n**Recommendation:** Remove the `RoomTimeline` interface and `findEarliestSlot`, and use `findEarliestSlotArr` everywhere. This eliminates approximately 45 lines of duplicated logic and reduces the surface area for inconsistencies.\n\n---\n\n### 10. SUGGESTION: The `strategy` Parameter is Stringly-Typed\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, line 277\n\n```typescript\nstrategy: string\n```\n\nThis should be a union type:\n\n```typescript\nstrategy: 'prefer-early' | 'prefer-small-room' | 'prefer-large-room'\n```\n\nNote also that the `'prefer-early'` and `'prefer-small-room'` strategies produce identical behavior. Both filter rooms by `sortedRooms.filter(r => r.capacity >= attendees)`, and `sortedRooms` is already sorted ascending by capacity. The `'prefer-early'` strategy does not do anything different from `'prefer-small-room'`. This means only two distinct strategies are actually explored, not three.\n\n---\n\n### Summary of Findings\n\n| # | Severity | Issue |\n|---|----------|-------|\n| 1 | Critical | Gap overlap check is asymmetric -- `slot.start - gap` may reject valid placements when inserting before an existing event |\n| 2 | Critical (cleared) | `timeline.pop()` in backtracking is correct but fragile; needs a comment |\n| 3 | Important | Tiebreaker logic in `orderedEvents.sort()` is dead code due to `indexOf` always differing |\n| 4 | Important | `queue.sort()` inside Kahn's algorithm loop degrades to O(V^2 log V) |\n| 5 | Important | Backtracking disabled for >15 events without documentation or fallback |\n| 6 | Important | Transitive dependent count BFS is O(V*(V+E)) and its result is never used |\n| 7 | Suggestion | Backtracking prematurely stops exploring rooms when preferred room works |\n| 8 | Suggestion | Test suite missing edge cases (0-duration events, nonexistent preferred room, all-unschedulable) |\n| 9 | Suggestion | Code duplication between `findEarliestSlot` and `findEarliestSlotArr` |\n| 10 | Suggestion | `'prefer-early'` and `'prefer-small-room'` strategies are functionally identical |\n\n### What Was Done Well\n\n- The interfaces exactly match the TASK.md specification.\n- Cycle detection with DFS and self-reference check is correct and throws as required.\n- Prerequisite gap enforcement is implemented (the gap applies between prerequisite end and dependent start).\n- Non-existent prerequisites are gracefully ignored.\n- The multi-strategy approach with a backtracking fallback is a thoughtful design for the \"batch optimization\" requirement.\n- The test suite covers all the major requirements: capacity, time window, gaps, prerequisites, cycles, preferred rooms, batch optimization, overlap validation, and complex multi-constraint scenarios.\n- Clean TypeScript with strict mode enabled and proper type exports."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a1eeb03 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 32143\ntool_uses: 8\nduration_ms: 94799</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9e2ab351-e605-4df1-ad78-9a0d3c5d65ed","uuid":"a0f8f6ee-24f5-49d1-bae1-4e880650afea","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review the implementation of the constraint-based event scheduler in /workspace/src/index.ts and the tests in /workspace/src/scheduler.test.ts. The task requirements are in /workspace/TASK.md.\n\nFocus on:\n1. Correctness: Does the implementation satisfy all scheduling rules?\n2. Edge cases: Are there any missed edge cases?\n3. Code quality: Is the code clean and well-organized?\n4. The batch optimization requirement: Does it actually maximize scheduled events?\n5. Any bugs or issues that could cause test failures","agentId":"a1eeb03","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All tests pass, TypeScript compiles cleanly, and lint passes. Now let me do a thorough deep-dive review of the implementation.\n\n---\n\n## Code Review: Constraint-Based Event Scheduler\n\n### Overall Assessment\n\nAll 30 tests pass, the project compiles without errors, and lint is clean. The implementation in `/workspace/src/index.ts` is a reasonable solution that uses a multi-strategy greedy approach combined with a bounded backtracking solver. The test suite in `/workspace/src/scheduler.test.ts` covers the major requirements well. That said, I have identified several issues -- some of which are correctness bugs that could surface with inputs not covered by the current tests, and others that are structural or performance concerns.\n\n---\n\n### 1. CRITICAL: Gap Symmetry Bug in `findEarliestSlot` and `findEarliestSlotArr`\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 174 and 553\n\nBoth slot-finding functions use this overlap check:\n\n```typescript\nif (candidateStart < slot.end + gap && candidateEnd > slot.start - gap) {\n```\n\nThe condition `candidateEnd > slot.start - gap` is incorrect. The gap is a minimum spacing between the *end* of one event and the *start* of the next. It should not be applied symmetrically on both sides of existing slots. The correct check for whether a candidate conflicts with an existing slot (i.e., they are closer than `gap` apart) is:\n\n```typescript\nif (candidateStart < slot.end + gap && candidateEnd + gap > slot.start) {\n```\n\nOr equivalently, the non-overlapping condition should be:\n- candidate ends before slot starts (with gap): `candidateEnd + gap <= slot.start`\n- candidate starts after slot ends (with gap): `candidateStart >= slot.end + gap`\n\nThe current code subtracts `gap` from `slot.start`, which means if a candidate event tries to fit *before* an existing event, it must end `gap` minutes before the existing event starts -- that part is correct in intent. But the issue is subtle: consider `candidateEnd > slot.start - gap`. If `gap = 0`, this correctly checks for strict non-overlap. But when `gap > 0`, the expression `slot.start - gap` can cause the algorithm to reject valid placements or, more importantly, it treats the gap as needing to be enforced on *both* sides when the algorithm then pushes `candidateStart = slot.end + gap`, effectively double-counting the gap constraint in certain edge cases.\n\nIn practice, this is likely masked because the algorithm always starts from `earliestStart` and moves forward, so it predominantly encounters the `candidateStart < slot.end + gap` branch. However, if events are not placed in chronological order (which can happen in the backtracking solver), a candidate that should fit into a gap *before* an existing event may be incorrectly rejected.\n\n**Recommendation:** Replace the overlap check with the clearer form:\n\n```typescript\nif (candidateStart < slot.end + gap && candidateEnd > slot.start - gap) {\n```\n\nShould be:\n\n```typescript\nif (!(candidateEnd + gap <= slot.start || candidateStart >= slot.end + gap)) {\n```\n\nWhich simplifies to:\n\n```typescript\nif (candidateEnd + gap > slot.start && candidateStart < slot.end + gap) {\n```\n\nThis ensures the gap is applied symmetrically and correctly: the candidate must be at least `gap` minutes away from any existing slot on either side.\n\n---\n\n### 2. CRITICAL: Backtracking `timeline.pop()` Assumes Last-In-First-Out Ordering\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, line 477\n\n```typescript\ntimeline.push({ start: slotStart, end: slotStart + event.duration });\n// ... recursive call ...\nassignments.delete(event.id);\ntimeline.pop();\n```\n\nThe backtracking solver adds a slot with `timeline.push(...)` and removes it with `timeline.pop()`. This only works correctly if the most recently pushed slot is always the last element -- i.e., no other slot is pushed on top of it before the pop occurs. In the recursive `solve` call, the function iterates over `schedulable` events and for each one tries multiple rooms. When a slot is pushed and then `solve` recurses, the recursive call could push additional slots on the *same* timeline array. Those recursive slots are popped within their own frames, so by the time control returns, the pushed slot should indeed be the last element.\n\nThis is actually correct due to the stack-based recursion pattern: each recursive frame pushes, recurses deeper (which pushes and pops its own slots), then pops. However, there is a subtle issue: the code iterates over `schedulable` events in a `for` loop and tries each one. When it places event A in room X and recurses, the recursive call might also try to place event B in room X (pushing onto the same timeline). But event B's slot is popped before returning, so event A's slot remains last. This is correct.\n\n**Verdict:** This is actually safe, but it is fragile. A comment explaining why `pop()` is valid here would improve maintainability.\n\n---\n\n### 3. IMPORTANT: Topological Sort Comparison is Unstable/Redundant\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 289-297\n\n```typescript\nconst orderedEvents = [...sortedEvents].sort((a, b) => {\n  const idxA = sortedEvents.indexOf(a);\n  const idxB = sortedEvents.indexOf(b);\n  if (idxA !== idxB) return idxA - idxB;\n  const depA = dependentCount.get(a.id) || 0;\n  const depB = dependentCount.get(b.id) || 0;\n  if (depA !== depB) return depB - depA;\n  return b.duration - a.duration;\n});\n```\n\nThe `indexOf` comparison will always return different values for different objects (assuming no duplicates), so the first branch `if (idxA !== idxB) return idxA - idxB` will always be taken. The dependent count and duration tiebreakers are dead code. This means the \"ordering\" by dependent count that `greedySchedule` computes (lines 206-239, including a BFS for every event) is entirely wasted computation.\n\nTo actually use the tiebreakers, the events at the same topological level need to be identified. One approach: assign a topological \"depth\" to each event and sort by depth first, then by dependent count and duration within the same depth.\n\n**Recommendation:** Either remove the dead-code tiebreaker logic or fix the sort to use topological depth rather than array index.\n\n---\n\n### 4. IMPORTANT: `topologicalSort` Has O(n^2) Performance Due to `queue.sort()` Inside the Loop\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, line 106\n\n```typescript\nwhile (queue.length > 0) {\n  queue.sort();\n  const id = queue.shift()!;\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\nSorting the queue on every iteration converts Kahn's algorithm from O(V+E) to O(V^2 log V). For the 15-event cap on backtracking this is irrelevant, but it is poor algorithmic practice. The sort also has no clear purpose -- it lexicographically orders event IDs, which produces deterministic output but is not a meaningful scheduling heuristic.\n\n**Recommendation:** Use a priority queue or simply remove the sort if determinism is not a requirement.\n\n---\n\n### 5. IMPORTANT: Backtracking is Gated Behind `sortedEvents.length <= 15`\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, line 522\n\n```typescript\nif (sortedEvents.length <= 15) {\n  solve([...sortedEvents]);\n}\n```\n\nFor inputs with more than 15 events, the backtracking solver is silently skipped, meaning the \"batch optimization\" requirement (maximizing scheduled events) relies entirely on the three greedy strategies. This is a pragmatic performance tradeoff, but it should be documented. The task requirement states: \"The scheduler should maximize the number of events scheduled. Simply fitting events in order is not sufficient.\" For large inputs, the greedy-only approach may not maximize scheduled events.\n\n**Recommendation:** Add a comment explaining the tradeoff. Consider a middle ground such as applying backtracking only to the subset of events that failed greedy scheduling (rather than all events).\n\n---\n\n### 6. IMPORTANT: `greedySchedule` Recomputes Transitive Dependents Inefficiently\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 226-239\n\n```typescript\nfor (const e of sortedEvents) {\n  const visited = new Set<string>();\n  const queue = [e.id];\n  while (queue.length > 0) {\n    const curr = queue.shift()!;\n    for (const dep of reverseDeps.get(curr) || []) {\n      if (!visited.has(dep)) {\n        visited.add(dep);\n        queue.push(dep);\n      }\n    }\n  }\n  dependentCount.set(e.id, visited.size);\n}\n```\n\nThis computes a BFS from every event to count transitive dependents -- O(V * (V+E)) in the worst case. Since the result is never actually used (see issue 3), this is wasted work. If the tiebreaker is fixed, a simple in-degree count or depth-based approach would suffice and be more efficient.\n\n---\n\n### 7. SUGGESTION: Preferred Room Logic May Prematurely Break in Backtracking\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 489-490\n\n```typescript\n// For preferred room, if it worked, don't try others\nif (room.id === event.preferredRoom) break;\n```\n\nIn the backtracking solver, when the preferred room works, the code breaks out of the room loop immediately. This means the solver never explores alternative room placements for this event, even if placing it in a non-preferred room might allow more total events to be scheduled. Since the task states that `preferredRoom` is \"a hint, not a hard constraint,\" the optimization goal (maximize events) should take priority over room preference in the backtracking solver.\n\n**Recommendation:** Remove this `break` in the backtracking solver to allow full exploration, or at least try the preferred room first but still explore alternatives.\n\n---\n\n### 8. SUGGESTION: Missing Test Coverage for Edge Cases\n\nThe test suite is solid but misses a few scenarios:\n\n- **Gap between prerequisite and dependent across different rooms**: The test at line 202 uses two rooms, but does not verify that the gap is applied even when the prerequisite and dependent are in *different* rooms. (The implementation does handle this correctly, but a test would confirm the intent.)\n\n- **Multiple prerequisites for a single event**: The complex scenario test has this (closing depends on workshop and breakout), but there is no isolated unit test for multiple prerequisites where the latest-finishing prerequisite determines the start time.\n\n- **Events with 0-minute duration**: The task does not prohibit it, and the scheduler would likely handle it, but no test exercises this boundary.\n\n- **All events unschedulable**: A test where every event exceeds every room's capacity would verify the \"everything goes to unscheduled\" path.\n\n- **Preferred room that does not exist**: An event referencing a `preferredRoom` ID that is not in the rooms list. The current implementation handles this gracefully (the preference is simply ignored), but a test would document this behavior.\n\n---\n\n### 9. SUGGESTION: Code Duplication Between `findEarliestSlot` and `findEarliestSlotArr`\n\n**Files:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 147-191 and 537-566\n\nThese two functions are nearly identical. The only difference is that `findEarliestSlot` takes a `RoomTimeline` object while `findEarliestSlotArr` takes a raw array. The `RoomTimeline` wrapper adds no value since it just wraps a `slots` array.\n\n**Recommendation:** Remove the `RoomTimeline` interface and `findEarliestSlot`, and use `findEarliestSlotArr` everywhere. This eliminates approximately 45 lines of duplicated logic and reduces the surface area for inconsistencies.\n\n---\n\n### 10. SUGGESTION: The `strategy` Parameter is Stringly-Typed\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, line 277\n\n```typescript\nstrategy: string\n```\n\nThis should be a union type:\n\n```typescript\nstrategy: 'prefer-early' | 'prefer-small-room' | 'prefer-large-room'\n```\n\nNote also that the `'prefer-early'` and `'prefer-small-room'` strategies produce identical behavior. Both filter rooms by `sortedRooms.filter(r => r.capacity >= attendees)`, and `sortedRooms` is already sorted ascending by capacity. The `'prefer-early'` strategy does not do anything different from `'prefer-small-room'`. This means only two distinct strategies are actually explored, not three.\n\n---\n\n### Summary of Findings\n\n| # | Severity | Issue |\n|---|----------|-------|\n| 1 | Critical | Gap overlap check is asymmetric -- `slot.start - gap` may reject valid placements when inserting before an existing event |\n| 2 | Critical (cleared) | `timeline.pop()` in backtracking is correct but fragile; needs a comment |\n| 3 | Important | Tiebreaker logic in `orderedEvents.sort()` is dead code due to `indexOf` always differing |\n| 4 | Important | `queue.sort()` inside Kahn's algorithm loop degrades to O(V^2 log V) |\n| 5 | Important | Backtracking disabled for >15 events without documentation or fallback |\n| 6 | Important | Transitive dependent count BFS is O(V*(V+E)) and its result is never used |\n| 7 | Suggestion | Backtracking prematurely stops exploring rooms when preferred room works |\n| 8 | Suggestion | Test suite missing edge cases (0-duration events, nonexistent preferred room, all-unschedulable) |\n| 9 | Suggestion | Code duplication between `findEarliestSlot` and `findEarliestSlotArr` |\n| 10 | Suggestion | `'prefer-early'` and `'prefer-small-room'` strategies are functionally identical |\n\n### What Was Done Well\n\n- The interfaces exactly match the TASK.md specification.\n- Cycle detection with DFS and self-reference check is correct and throws as required.\n- Prerequisite gap enforcement is implemented (the gap applies between prerequisite end and dependent start).\n- Non-existent prerequisites are gracefully ignored.\n- The multi-strategy approach with a backtracking fallback is a thoughtful design for the \"batch optimization\" requirement.\n- The test suite covers all the major requirements: capacity, time window, gaps, prerequisites, cycles, preferred rooms, batch optimization, overlap validation, and complex multi-constraint scenarios.\n- Clean TypeScript with strict mode enabled and proper type exports."}],"totalDurationMs":94799,"totalTokens":32143,"totalToolUseCount":8,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":403,"cache_read_input_tokens":28145,"output_tokens":3594,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":403,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[]}}}
